AGI - More and less born in Italy. And a five-time worker comes out of the world of work after having a son. In 2023 we reached a new historical minimum in a country that is now stably firm under 400 thousand units, with a decrease of 3.6% compared to the previous year. Women choose not to have children or have fewer than they would like: the average number of children per woman, in fact, is 1,20, showing a decline compared to 2022 (1,24). Very far from the date of 2010, when the average number of children per woman had reached the relative maximum recorded in the last twenty years, equal to 1,44. According to Save The Children who presented the report on Maternity in Italy, The birth contraction that accompanies Italy for decades now also involves the foreign component of the population (in 2023 minus 3 thousand born compared to the previous year).
&nbsp;
Italy is also the European country with the highest average age of women at the time of the birth of the first child (31.6 years), with a significant percentage of first born mothers over 40 (8.9%, lower rate only than that of Spain). The average age of mothers at birth remains almost unchanged compared to the previous year (32.5 years in 2023 and 32.4 in 2022). Save the Children's report entitled "Le Equilibriste, la maternity in Italia" published today a few days from Mother's Day, draws a balance of the endless challenges women in Italy face when they choose to become mothers. As every year, the study also includes the Madri Index, developed by Istat for Save the Children, a ranking of Italian regions where for mothers it is easier to live. Also this year, the Index indicates the Autonomous Province of Bolzano to lead the territories friends of the mothers, followed by Emilia-Romagna and Tuscany, while the tail light is the Basilicata, preceded at the bottom of the ranking, from Campania and Sicily.
&nbsp;
If the postponement of maternity and low fecundity is the result of numerous causes, the data reveals that the more the participation of women in the labour market increases, the more the rate of fertility increases. An element to be taken into consideration, in a labour market that still has a very strong gender gap. From the data of the Save the Children Report, it emerges that in Italy the female employment rate (aged 15-64 years) was 52.5% in 2023, a lower value than the European Union average (65.8%) of 13 percentage points. The difference between the employment rate of men and women in our country, in the same year, was 17.9 percentage points, much more marked than the differences observed at EU27 (9.4 percentage points) and second, very little, only to Greece, where the difference is 18 percentage points.
&nbsp;
For women, the theme of balancing work and family remains critical for those in their family who carry out unpaid care. An indicator of the difficulties that mothers face in reconciling family and working commitments is the number of women employed between 25 and 54 years of age: in the face of a female employment rate of 63.8%, women without children who work reach 68.7%, while only a little more than half of those with two or more children are employed (57.8%). On the contrary, for men of the same age, the total employment rate is 83.7%, with a variation ranging from 77.3% for those without children, up to 91.3% for those with a younger son and 91.6% for those with two or more.
&nbsp;
Many territorial disparities: in the South of Italy for women, the occupation stops at 48.9% for those without children (it is 79.8% to the north and 74.4% to the center) and falls to 42% in the presence of children minors reaching 40% for women with two or more children minors (to the north are 73.2% and to the center 68.3%). The same disparity is also noted for men, although with different values: in the meridian the men without children employed reach 61.5%, (they are 86.7% in the North and 81.3% in the Centre), while those with children reach 82.8% (96.7% in the North and 94.5% in the Centre).
&nbsp;
It is evident that the birth of a child affects gender disparity in the world of work. To resign are mainly mothers, to the first son and within his first year of life. During 2022, in fact, a total of 61,391 were made of voluntary resignation for parents of children aged 0-3 throughout the national territory, up 17.1% compared to the previous year. 72.8% of the total (equal to 44.699) covers women, while 27.2% concern men (equal to 16.692), with a higher growth than the female ones compared to the previous year. Again this year in the motivations between men and women for the convalid, a significant difference emerges. For women, in fact, the main one is the difficulty in reconciling work and care of the child: 41.7% attributed this difficulty to the lack of assistance services, while 21.9% indicated problems related to the organization of work.
&nbsp;
Overall, care-related challenges account for 63.6% of all validation motivations provided by mother workers. For men, however, the predominant motivation is of a professional nature: 78.9% said that the end of the working relationship was due to a change of company and only 7.1% reported care needs of children. Among the most "friendly regions of the mothers", the Autonomous Province of Bolzano (115,255), Emilia-Romagna (110,530), respectively in the first and second position of the list. Immediately behind Tuscany, that compared to the last edition earns a position (109,239) and stands at third place.
&nbsp;
Although compared to the previous year, the Italian situation has improved both from an absolute point of view, and from a point of view of territorial gap, the regions of the Mezzogiorno, continue to position themselves all below the Italian reference value, with some particularly far from the quota 100. Calabria (92,671), Apulia (92,085), Sicily (91,050), Campania (89,474) and Basilicata (87,441), tail lighthouse, occupy the last places of the General Index without almost overturning regarding the last edition, with an exchange of positions between Puglia (18 ) that loses a position and Calabria (17 ) that earns it. Relegated to the bottom of the Index, these regions more than others, discourage the lack of investments in the territory that result in a structural shortage of services and work. Among the regions that are better than the previous year, the Lazio that passes from 13 to 8 place earning 5 positions and Lombardy that from 8 is at 4 .
&nbsp;
The Marches (102,488), Piedmont (100,979), Abruzzo (100,504) and Liguria (100,321), occupy the first places in the Job area. Regions where, for mothers the world of work, in fact, is more accessible and where the number of resignations or that of the reductions of working hours not voluntary after the birth of one or more children are lower. On the other hand, Puglia (84,667), the Autonomous Province of Trento (84,356), Sicily (81,567) and Campania (81,535) are the least virtuous ones, occupying respectively from the eighteenth to the last position. The data also shows that in Italy, while full-time work is more common among men than women, the opposite happens for part-time work. In general in our country only 6.6% of the men who work, do so in part time, compared to 31.3% of the workers, who for half the cases (15.4%) suffers an involuntary part-time.
&nbsp;
Among those who have children, the percentage of women employed in parttime (36.7%) increases considerably compared with those without children (23.5%). Among the men, instead, we pass from 8.7% for those who have no children to 4.6% for the fathers. Coming out of Italy, it emerges that from 2000 to today, France is the only European country remained stably close to the threshold of two children per woman, although from 2015 the country has seen gradually descend its rate of fertility, with an exception between 2020 and 2021 when the average number of children per woman has grown, and in 2022 stands on 1,79 children per woman. Its approach is focused on an articulated financial support system for families and the guarantee of access to quality childcare services and calibrated on different family needs. Finland, despite a decline in population growth in the course of 2022, experienced a sharp rise in the birth rate between 2019 and 2021.
&nbsp;
The country adopted in 2022 one of the reforms on the most innovative leave in Europe, which provides for the symmetric allocation of leave quotas for each parent, with the possibility of transferring part of the share to the other parent, a total parental leave and greater flexibility in use. Access to early childhood services is also guaranteed to a very high percentage of children, especially in the range between 2 and 3 years (69.6%). In Germany the rate of fertility increased between 2020 and 2021, but had a drastic decline again in 2022, passing from 1,58 to 1,46 children per woman. Here, in addition to the economic support for children and the possibility to take part-time parental leave while working for the rest of the time thus compensating for the loss of income to 67%, children from 1 year of age are entitled to a place in a kindergarten or in a similar service.
&nbsp;
Finally, the Czech Republic since 2011 has progressively increased the rate of fertility, up to 1,83 children per woman in 2021; in 2022 as and more than in other European countries, even here the rate has come down. The country, with a rate of participation in childcare services 0-2 years of 6% in 2020, favoured a traditional care model, favouring long periods of abstention from the work of mothers. Meanwhile, Italy recorded fertility rates constantly below 1.5 with a decline started in 2007 and never interrupted (if not for 1 decimal point between 2020 and 2021).
